Perhaps this is a MATLAB problem. In MATLAB, there is no way that I can 
find to delete the C++ Cantera object when the MATLAB &#39;shadow&#39; object 
is deleted (cleared).  So if you create lots of Cantera objects in the 
MATLAB workspace, it can consume memory that is not released even if 
you type &#39;clear all&#39;.  I have provided a function &#39;cleanup&#39; that 
deletes ALL Cantera objects.  If you use &#39;cleanup&#39;, you must also clear 
all Cantera objects from the MATLAB workspace, since they cannot be 
used once the underlying C++ objects are deleted.

Or it could be a problem due to using MATLAB 6.5, since the Windows 
Cantera MATLAB toolbox was compiled with MATLAB 7.

If MATLAB gives you problems, you could do your calculation in Python, 
which has better capabilities for memory management.

Dave



